def clean_missing_category(df):
    """
    Fill categorical missing value in abrscore, home, ethnic and sex.
    """
    df.loc[df.abrscore.isnull(), 'abrscore'] = "NOT_ABR" # Not Absentee Ballot Return
    df.loc[df.home.isnull(), 'home'] = "N" # not home owner
    df.loc[df.ethnic.isnull(), 'ethnic'] = "NN" # not known
    #df.loc[df.sex.isnull(), 'sex'] = "NN" # not know

Some Observations:

  • frequent voters and voters voted in 03/05/2013, 05/21/2013 and 06/07/2016 support candidate_b slightly higher than candidate_a.
  • More voters from demplus and party_D support candidate_b than candidate_a
  • More voters not from repplus support candidate_b than candidate_a, more voters from party_R support candidate_a than candidate_b.
  • This implies candidate_a might be a republican candidate, and candidate_b might be a democrat candidate.
  • More unmarried voters and rental voters support candidate_b.
  • Voters have overlapped age distributions, candidate_a have more younger supporters.
  • All above differences are not significant.

Feature Correlations¶

In [128]:
def binary_category_to_numeric(df):
    """
    Change binary category data to 0/1 numeric features.
    """
    df['support'] = df['support'].map({'candidate_b':0, 'candidate_a':1}) # 0 for support b, 1 for a
    df['demplus'] = df['demplus'].map({'N':0, 'Y':1}) # 0 for N, 1 for Y
    df['repplus'] = df['repplus'].map({'N':0, 'Y':1}) # 0 for N, 1 for Y
    df['ismarried'] = df['ismarried'].map({'N':0, 'Y':1}) # 0 for N, 1 for Y
    df['home'] = df['home'].map({'N':0, 'H':1}) # 0 for N, 1 for H
    df['renters'] = df['renters'].map({'N':0, 'Y':1}) # 0 for N, 1 for Y
    df['sex'] = df['sex'].map({'F':0, 'M':1}) # 0 for F, 1 for M

3.2 Random Forest Model¶

  • Random Forest is effective at discovering nonlinear relationships.
  • Random Forest has better interpretability, can help us get insight of feature importance.
  • Random Forest is fast and no feature selection is needed at current stage.
  • Can use predict probability (predict_proba) to give out class probability results for candidate A.

from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, f1_score, precision_score, recall_score, classification_report

def get_metrics(y_test, y_predicted):  
    """
    Return metric scores for the classification model.
    """
    # true positives / (true positives+false positives)
    precision = precision_score(y_test, y_predicted, pos_label=None,
                                    average='weighted')             
    # true positives / (true positives + false negatives)
    recall = recall_score(y_test, y_predicted, pos_label=None,
                              average='weighted')
    
    # harmonic mean of precision and recall
    f1 = f1_score(y_test, y_predicted, pos_label=None, average='weighted')
    
    # true positives + true negatives/ total
    accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_predicted)
    return accuracy, precision, recall, f1

Feature Importance¶

In [145]:
def plot_feature_importance(model, features, X_train, n_feature_plot, size):
    """
    Plot feature importance.
    
    param n_features_plot: how many features in the final plot.
    """
    importances = model.feature_importances_
    indices = np.argsort(importances)[::-1]
    indices_plot = indices[:n_feature_plot]

    # Print the feature ranking
    print("Feature ranking:")

    for f in range(X_train.shape[1]):
        print("%d. feature %s (%f)" % (f + 1, features[indices[f]], importances[indices[f]]))

    # Plot the feature importances of the forest
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))
    plt.title("Feature importances",size=16)
    plt.barh(range(n_feature_plot), importances[indices_plot], color="steelblue", align="center")
    plt.yticks(range(n_feature_plot), [features[index] for index in indices_plot], size=14), #{'rotate':45})
    plt.ylim([n_feature_plot,-1])
    plt.xticks(size=12)
    plt.show()

from sklearn.metrics import roc_curve, auc

def plot_roc_curve(model, X_test, size):

    y_prob = model.predict_proba(X_test)[:,1]

    fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y_test, y_prob, pos_label=1)
    auc_score = auc(fpr,tpr)
    plt.figure(figsize=(size,size))
    #fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y_test, y_prob, pos_label=1)
    plt.plot(np.arange(10)/9., np.arange(10)/9.)
    plt.plot(fpr,tpr)
    plt.xlabel('False Positive rate')
    plt.ylabel('True Positive rate')
    plt.title('AUC={0}'.format(auc_score))

from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix

def plot_confusion_matrix(cm, classes,
                          normalize=False,
                          title='Confusion matrix',
                          cmap=plt.cm.Blues):
    """
    This function prints and plots the confusion matrix.
    Normalization can be applied by setting `normalize=True`.
    """
    if normalize:
        cm = cm.astype('float') / cm.sum(axis=1)[:, np.newaxis]
        print("Normalized confusion matrix")
    else:
        print('Confusion matrix, without normalization')

    plt.imshow(cm, interpolation='nearest', cmap=cmap)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.colorbar()
    tick_marks = np.arange(len(classes))
    plt.xticks(tick_marks, classes, rotation=45)
    plt.yticks(tick_marks, classes)

    fmt = '.2f' if normalize else 'd'
    thresh = cm.max() / 2.
    for i, j in itertools.product(range(cm.shape[0]), range(cm.shape[1])):
        plt.text(j, i, format(cm[i, j], fmt),
                 horizontalalignment="center",
                 color="white" if cm[i, j] > thresh else "black")

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.ylabel('True label')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted label')

4. Modeling (with graph feature)¶

4.1 Feature Engineering - Simple Graph Statistic Feature¶

Statistical Features:

  • relation_count: count of relations ('sink's) in the graph data
  • relation_sum: sum of strength of all relationships
  • relation_mean: mean strength of relationship
In [189]:
dfg = df.copy() # dfg: df with graph features
In [190]:
def calc_relation_count(source_id):
    return graph_df[graph_df['source'] == source_id]['sink'].count()

def calc_relation_sum(source_id):
    return graph_df[graph_df['source'] == source_id]['relationship_score'].sum()

def calc_relation_mean(source_id):
    return graph_df[graph_df['source'] == source_id]['relationship_score'].mean()
In [191]:
dfg['relation_count'] = dfg['prim_id'].apply(lambda x: calc_relation_count(x))
dfg['relation_sum'] = dfg['prim_id'].apply(lambda x: calc_relation_sum(x))
dfg['relation_mean'] = dfg['prim_id'].apply(lambda x: calc_relation_mean(x))
dfg.loc[dfg.relation_mean.isnull(), 'relation_mean'] = 0

4.2 Feature Engineering - Support Candidate A Probability from Graph Relationships¶

First predict probability of support candidate A (prob_a) of each voter by previous random forest model (without graph feature). Then create two new features:

  • relation_prob_a_rf_avg: for a particular source, this is the average of sink_prob_a_rf for all related sinks.
  • relation_prob_a_rf_weighted_avg: for a particular source, this is the weighted average of sink_prob_a_rf for all related sinks. Here 'weight' is the strength of the relationship.

Note that graph_df has more voters prim_id than that in voters_df, for those without voters feature, I'll assign a prob_a = 0.5.

Process voters_df¶

In [197]:
def binary_category_to_numeric2(df):
    """
    Change binary category data to 0/1 numeric features.
    """
    #df['support'] = df['support'].map({'candidate_b':0, 'candidate_a':1}) # 0 for support b, 1 for a
    df['demplus'] = df['demplus'].map({'N':0, 'Y':1}) # 0 for N, 1 for Y
    df['repplus'] = df['repplus'].map({'N':0, 'Y':1}) # 0 for N, 1 for Y
    df['ismarried'] = df['ismarried'].map({'N':0, 'Y':1}) # 0 for N, 1 for Y
    df['home'] = df['home'].map({'N':0, 'H':1}) # 0 for N, 1 for H
    df['renters'] = df['renters'].map({'N':0, 'Y':1}) # 0 for N, 1 for Y
    df['sex'] = df['sex'].map({'F':0, 'M':1}) # 0 for F, 1 for M
    df.loc[df.sex.isnull(), 'sex'] = 0.5 # set not known sex = 0.5

Create relation_prob_a_rf_avg feature¶

In [224]:
def calc_relation_prob_avg(source_id, prob_type):
    return graph_df[graph_df['source'] == source_id][prob_type].mean()

dfg['relation_prob_a_rf_avg'] = dfg['prim_id'].apply(lambda x: calc_relation_prob_avg(x, 'sink_prob_a_rf'))
dfg.loc[dfg.relation_prob_a_rf_avg.isnull(), 'relation_prob_a_rf_avg'] = 0.5

Create relation_prob_a_rf_weighted_avg¶

For a particular source, this is the weighted average of sink_prob_a_rf for all related sinks. Here 'weight' is the strength of the relationship.

In [225]:
def calc_relation_prob_a_weighted_avg(source_id, prob_type):
    df_ = graph_df[graph_df['source'] == source_id]
    sum_ = 0
    prob_sum = 0
    for i in range(df_.shape[0]):
        rel = df_.iloc[i]['relationship_score']
        prob = df_.iloc[i][prob_type]
        sum_ += rel
        prob_sum += rel * prob
    
    if sum_ == 0:
        return 0.5
    return prob_sum / sum_

dfg['relation_prob_a_rf_weighted_avg'] = dfg['prim_id'].apply(lambda x: calc_relation_prob_a_weighted_avg(x, 'sink_prob_a_rf'))
